MAZDA SENDING CARS TO SIBERIA 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Wire Services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
TOKYO 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Mazda Motor Corp. said today it will begin exporting cars to the Soviet Union 
in June with a shipment of 210 Mazda model 323 cars bound for a timber complex 
in Siberia. 
</P>
<P>
Mazda will export the cars through C. Itoh &amp; Co., a Japanese trading 
company, which will pay Mazda cash for the cars, said Ken Haruki, a spokesman 
for Mazda. C. Itoh may receive timber in exchange for the cars, he said. 
</P>
<P>
The cars are to be sold to the timber complex in the city of Ilimsk, Siberia, 
the company said in a news release. 
</P>
<P>
Toyota, Nissan and Mitsubishi have exported vehicles to the Soviet Union. Japan 
exported a total of 4,600 vehicles to the Soviet Union last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
